    "categorySlug": "multi-agent",
    "categoryIcon": "graph",
    "title": "Orchestrator + Specialists",
    "difficulty": "advanced",
    "icon": "tree-structure",
    "description": "An orchestrator agent delegates tasks to specialist sub-agents automatically.",
    "guidance": "Multi-agent systems let you break complex tasks into specialist roles. The orchestrator acts as a router — it receives the user's request and decides which specialist(s) to engage.\n\nHow it works:\n1. The user's request goes to the orchestrator\n2. The orchestrator's instructions tell it which sub-agents exist and what each does\n3. The orchestrator calls the right sub-agent(s) — or handles simple queries itself\n4. Results are synthesized into a unified response\n\nSub-agents are defined independently and attached via the subAgents parameter. Each sub-agent can have its own tools, memory, and model.\n\nDesign tips:\n• Give each sub-agent a clear, non-overlapping specialization\n• The orchestrator's description should clearly enumerate when to use each sub-agent\n• Sub-agents can themselves have sub-agents (see Three-Level Hierarchy sample 031)\n• Add memory to the orchestrator to track what was delegated",
    "output": "Analyzing your request — routing to specialists...\n\n[MathAgent] The integral of x² from 0 to 3 is:\n∫₀³ x² dx = [x³/3]₀³ = (27/3) - (0/3) = 9\n\n[CodeAgent] Here's a BoxLang function to compute definite integrals numerically:\n\n    numeric function integrate( f, a, b, steps = 1000 ) {\n        h = ( b - a ) / steps\n        sum = 0\n        for ( var i = 0; i < steps; i++ ) {\n            x = a + ( i + 0.5 ) * h\n            sum += f( x )\n        }\n        return sum * h\n    }\n\n    // Usage:\n    result = integrate( (x) => x^2, 0, 3 )\n    println( result )  // ≈ 9.0\n\n[Orchestrator] Both specialists have responded. The mathematical answer is 9 (exact), and the BoxLang implementation above uses the midpoint Riemann sum method for numerical approximation.",
    "docsUrl": "https://ai.ortusbooks.com/main-components/agents/hierarchy.md",
    "provider": "openai"
}
*/

// Specialist agents — each is an expert in its domain
mathAgent = aiAgent(
    name        : "MathAgent",
    description : "A mathematics expert that solves equations, calculus, and statistics problems",
    instructions: "You are a mathematics professor. Show your work step-by-step. Use proper mathematical notation."
)

codeAgent = aiAgent(
    name        : "CodeAgent",
    description : "A BoxLang programming expert that writes, reviews, and explains code",
    instructions: "You are a senior BoxLang developer. Always write clean, idiomatic BoxLang code with comments."
)

writingAgent = aiAgent(
    name        : "WritingAgent",
    description : "A technical writer that creates documentation, explanations, and content",
    instructions: "You are a technical writer. Create clear, well-structured content with appropriate headings and examples."
)

// Orchestrator — receives all requests and routes to the right specialist
orchestrator = aiAgent(
    name        : "Orchestrator",
    description : "Main coordinator that delegates to the right specialist",
    instructions: "
        You coordinate a team of specialists. For each user request, identify the best specialist(s):
        - MathAgent: mathematical calculations, equations, statistics, calculus
        - CodeAgent: programming questions, code examples, debugging, BoxLang syntax
        - WritingAgent: documentation, explanations, content creation
        Answer simple questions yourself. Delegate complex, domain-specific tasks to specialists.
        After delegation, synthesize the results into a unified, clear response.
    ",
    subAgents   : [ mathAgent, codeAgent, writingAgent ]
)

println( "Analyzing your request — routing to specialists..." )
println( "" )

// The orchestrator automatically decides which sub-agent(s) to use
response = orchestrator.run(
    "Calculate the integral of x² from 0 to 3, then write a BoxLang function that computes it numerically."
)
println( response )
